{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00222254711/1930072201/0789.xml":{"full_text":"DROUGHT CONDITIONS DECLARED TO BE WORST IN 40 YEARS\n\nVIRGINIAHIT\nHARO, ALSO\nMARYLAND\nMemphis, Tenn., Believed\nto Have Set World Mark\nWith 2 Per Cent Normal Rain\nThe country today continued in\nthe throes of a drought which, in\nsome sections, has smashed rec\nords of 40 years standing.\nDespite relief through showers\nto some parts of the nation, the\ndrought is unbroken. Irreparable\ndamage has been done to crops,\nmany cities and towns are suffer\ning from water shortage and heat\nhas taken its toll of lives.\nAn analysis of weather records\nby J. B. Kincer, chief of the Agri\ncultural Division of the United\nStates Weather Bureau, for Inter\nnational News Service, today re\nvealed the startling extent of the\nlong period of dry weather.\nSeriousness Recognised\nAlthough the seriousness of the\nsituation has become apparent\nonly recently, Kincer\u2019s records dis\nclosed that the drought actually\nbegan last December in an area\nextending from the lower Missis\nsippi Valley northeastward to\nMaryland. Every month has added\nto the deficiency of rainfall.\nThe most remarkable figure is\nthat for Memphis, Tenn. The\nweather bureau there reports that\nrainfall for the last nine weeks\nhas been but 2 per cent of nor\nmal. This is said to be an all\ntime record.\nOnly two sections of the coun\ntry apparently have escaped the\nblight of the drought. Although\nthere has been dry weather in\nSouth Atlantic States, relief came\nthrough showers, and suffering\nthere was less than many other\nplaces, Kincer said. New England\nalso has escaped, he said.\nWhile the path of the most ser\nious drought has moved from the\nlower Mississippi Valley through\nTennessee, Kentucky, southwest\nern Ohio, West Virginia, Virgin\nia and into Maryland, the middle\nwest also has suffered.\nPercentages to Normal\nThe percentage of rainfall to\nnormal during the growing sea\nson from May 20 to the latest\nrecord, July 21, is given by Kin\ncer as follows:\nSouthwestern Virginia, 23 per cent.\nWestern West Virginia, 19 per cent.\nEastern Kentucky, 22 to SO per cent.\nSouthern Indiana and Illinois, 35 to\nID per cent.\nWestern Tennesee, 8 per cent.\nSouthern Arkansas and Northern l/ou-\nJglana, 7 to 13 per cent.\nEastern Texas, 23 to 33 per Cent.\nNorthern Mississippi, 10 to 17 per\n\u2022\u2022nt.\nSouthern Kansas, 30 per cent.\nSoutheastern Nebraska and South-\nWestern lowa under 33 1-3 per eent.\nNorthern Indiana and Illinois. 50 to\nfl per cent.\nOhio, varied, 20 to 50 per cent.\nSouthern Michigan, 60 to 75 per cent.\nMinnesota. 66 2-3 per cent\nEastern lowa, 60 per cent to over\nBormal.\nNorth Dakota.' 40 to 67 per cent.\nEastern Montana, 30 to 65 per cent.\nSouth Dakota, under 50 per cent.\nVirginia Record Broken\nRecords of 40 years\u2019 standing\u2014\nthe earliest weather bureau rec\nords of all stations within States\n\u2014are broken by the drought in\nVirginia, West Virginia and Ken\ntucky. Maryland, Kincer found,\nexperienced almost as dry weather\nin 1925 and 1926. The nearest\napproach to the present dry\nperiod in Virginia, heigsaid, was\nin. 1894.\nThe severity of the heat is\nshown by the fact that maximum\ntemperatures ranged from 98 to\n104 from Thursday to Sunday in\nan area from Nebraska to the\nMiddle Atlantic coast.\nD. G.WNEES\nWIN PRIZES\nWashington boys took their\nshare of honors yesterday when\nhundreds of parents gathered at\nFort Myer to watch their sons\ncompete in the annual C. M. T. C.\ntrack and field meet.\nNearly 100 medals and trophies\nwere distributed among the cavalry\nstudents who participated. Among\nthe Washingtonians who won\nhonors were:\nMartin A. Klein, 1700 block F St.\nN. W., member of the Troop E's\nteam, which won the medicine\nball race and another which won\nthe caterpillar race: Bernard J.\nMcKeon, 700 block Webster St.\nN. W\u201e also a member of the win\nning medicine ball team; John\nKitteUe, 1700 block F St. N. W.,\nanother member of the winning\ncaterpillar team: Maynard J. Sim\nmons, jr\u201e 1800 block Kenyon St.\nN. W\u201e of the winning leap-frog\nrace team, and David P. Glassford,\nof the winning mounted tug-of\nwar team.\nNeighbors Flee When\nIced Fumes Spread\nStifling fumes released from an\nelectric refrigerator, which sprung\na leak in an apartment in the\nHighlands, 1900 block Connecticut\nAve. N. W.. last night caused sev\neral residents of adjoining apart\nments to flee until members of\nthe Fire Department Rescue\nSquad had repaired the leak.\nHears Looting Plot\nJ 9 I I\n>w v\nI B J I 1\nF J 11\nKMF .1\n1 JrT 9\nWHF >ls Ji\nL Hbi iik\u00ab\nk if\nip I'; T\nIH JB 4\n\"W Jf OBk\nI m il\nW\nBBBl\u00dflkr*\u2019 BBBHA f\niiMii ijWfjiiiMii. ii.iiiiiiaaiiiMMiii*iiini J d\u00dfm\n\u2014lnternational Newsreel\nPOLLY LUX\nA PLOT TO LOOT the home of Polly Lux, former\nFollies girl, was bared in New York court, when Natalie\nChadwick, former stage star now serving a term in\nAuburn Prison, confessed she had planned to ransack\nMiss Lux\u2019s home of SIO,OOO in furnishings.\nBRITISH PUZZLE\nOVER CRASH\nLONDON, July 22 (I.N.S.).\u2014 A\nshocked Britain today puzzled\nover the mysterious midair col\nlapse of an airtaxi over Meopham,\nKent, yesterday that flung six\npersons to instant death. Four\nwere members of the British aris\ntocracy.\nGovernment Investigators sent\nto the scene unearthed few clues\nas to the possible cause of the\nacciddent, with eyewitnesses able\nto offer only the meager informa\ntion that the plane apparently\nfell apart, and pieces of it\ndrifted down from various direc\ntions.\nThe party was returning from\nLe Touquet, fashionable French\nwatering place, where the week\nend had been spent as guests of\nthe countess of Dudley and of\nMrs. Henrik Loeffler.\nThose in the party included the\nViscountess Ednam. friend of\nthe Prince of Wales; the Mar\nquess of Dufferin and Ava, Mrs.\nHenrik Loeffler, Sir Edward\nSimons Ward, Lieut. Col. G. L. P.\nHenderson, pilot, and Charles\nShearing, assistant pilot.\nP. H. Reid, Editor,\n65, Dies in Detroit\nDETROIT, July 22 (1.N.5.).\nThe death of Philip H. Reid,\naged 65, retired journalist and\nformer managing editor of the\nDetroit Free Press, was attributed\nto the intense heat by doctors\ntoday.\nReid, a graduate of Brown Uni\nversity at Providence, R. 1., and\nonetime reporter for the Provi\ndence Journal, died suddenly late\nlast night. Although he had been\nin failing health, doctors said that\nthe high temperatures caused\nhim to succumb.\nNew Takoma Park\nSidewalks Planned\nPlans for laying sidewalks on a\ndozen streets in Takoma Park,\nMd., were approved at a meeting\nof Takoma Park citizens held last\nnight at the firehouse and com\nmunity center.\nThe paving program was out\nlined by Peter Remsen, chairman\nof the street committee, and won\nalmost unanimous approval. A\npromise that the council would\nconsider the matter was given by\nMayor Ben G. Davis'.\nHELD AS FORGER\nFREDERICKSBURG, Va\u201e July\n22.\u2014Harold Hodge Was taken to\nthe Lancaster jail to await ac\ntion of the grand jury in Sep\ntember on the charge of a fo.g\nery, after a hearing before Jus\ntice Chilton.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\n300 Parents Visit\nFort Hunt Trainees\nOver 300 parents, friends and\nguests visited Camp Fort Hunt\nyesterday, where 22 Howard Uni\nversity and a number of Wilber\nforce University students are\ntraining.\nThe program consisted of close\norder drill by company \u201cA\u201d, Indi\nvidual competitive drill, shelter\ntent pitching, firing of the\nBrowning machine gun and au\ntomatic rifle and an inspection.\nMajor F. A. Byrne is command\ning officer.\nThousands Watch Trainmen Clear Tracks\n\nP| 'MH\nWS <sHAs w vB\nOjfe. -A iff\nwl I** 7 i mJK 1 i\njf BMP*\u2019*\"\nw* 1\nBH\nS \u2018I |rp|i Ji--* fl\nRSWHHT Z- 3\u2014| JW 3J\u2014F WBFWSHSHB 'WMHMHMHBIMHM:MHHHR\nt \u2014lnternational Newereel\nSCENE. OF WRECK AT ELIZABETH N. J.\u2014loo INJURED\nTHOUSANDS looked on while trainmen worked to\nclear the tracks at Elizabeth, N. J., after a wreck in\nwhich 100 persons were injured. The Pennsylvania\nMOSES TO KEEP\nCAMPAIGN\nFOOT\nChairman of Senate Group\nExpected to Tour West to\nLine Up G. 0. P. Candidates\nSenator Moses (R.), of New\nHampshire, will preside at a\nmeeting of the Republican sena\ntorial campaign committee this\nmorning at which his chairman\nship will be confirmed, political\nforecasters last night said.\nFollowing his re-election to this\ncommittee post, Moses will make\na swing around the Western\nStates, but his purpose was well\ndescribed by friends close to the\nSenator, as follows:\n\u201cTo assist in the election of\nRepublicans regardless of their\npersonal or non-political com\nplexion.**\nIt was recalled here last night\nthat last year about this time\nPresident Hoover called Moses\nfrom his New Hampshire retreat\nin the White Mountains to the\nchairmanship of the Republican\nsenatorial committee.\nRegardless of the Senator\u2019s\nfriendship for Claudius H. Hus\nton, chairman of the Republican\nnational committee, whose resig\nnation has been forecast for the\nlast month, and recent rumblings\nin Republican ranks of dissatis\nfaction at his continuance at the\nhead of the senatorial campaign\ncommittee because of his \u201csons of\nthe wild jackass\u201d reference to\nWestern Republicans, Moses still\nremains an ardent supporter of\nthe Administration and any\nbarnstorming he may do in the\nFar West will be in the interest\nof the Republican party nomi\nnees. regardless of what group or\nfaction they may affiliate with.\nMan and Wife Hurt\nIn Crash Near T-B\nWhen the automobile in which\nthey were riding was in collision\nwith another car near TB. Md..\nlast night, George J. Byrne, 51,\nand his wife, Mrs. Estelle Byrne,\n34, 1600 block Massachusetts Ave.\nS. E., suffered lacerations and\nbruises.\nThe Injured couple were taken\nto Casualty Hosiptal by Fred\nCrismond, 1500 block A St. N. E.,\nand after treatment were per\nmitted to go home.\nWoman, 66, Found\nDead at Her Home\nA combination of old age and\nthe heat caused the death of Mary\nStewart. 66. colored, of the 700\nblock Smith\u2019s Row N. W., it was\nreported.\nThe aged woman was found\ndead in her home last night by\npolice after neighbors, alarmed at\nnot seeing the woman through\nout the day, notified authorities.\nTht National Dally\nRudy Valee, Radio Star, Visits Old Home Town\nS -z\nJal -v'-\n~r x\n\nf i HF dr j\n'g V ~'Z\nI I 1 W I\n1h\u00ab 4 U\n1 p 'T- 2 B J ,C.\"'\n\u25a0C- X. -x.'\nK i-.\n1 t 4 V H t\u2019 1r\n'I\nFATHER RUDY MOTHER\nWomen Demand Dresses\nShort, Will Get \u2019Em\nNEW YORK, July 22.\u2014\u201c Long\nskirts and dragging, irregular,\nawkward hemlines which are\ndifficult to wear for daytime\nwill have no place in fashion\nfor fall. Women want their\nskirts short enough to be com\nfortable. They want easy-to\nwear dresses. And of course,\nthey are going to get what they\nwant.\u201d\nThus spoke Amos Parrish, noted\nfashion authority, in opening the\nsecond day\u2019s sessions of the fash\nion merchandise clinic now being\nheld at the Ritz-Carlton Hotel,\nOwners and executives of 127\nleading department stores and\nspecialty shops are attending the\nfour-day clinic, held in advance\nof the fall buying and selling\nseason. Fashions in apparel and\naccessories for the fall and win-\nflier was derailed when it struck an automobile. It\ncarried the vehicle 500 feet before leaving the tracks.\nI\nTUESDAY, JULY 22, \u2018IO3O\nter season, selected on the basis\nof fashion analysis methods de\nveloped by Amos Parrish, are re\nported and Illustrated in the\nclinic. Mr. Parrish predicted to\nday:\n\u201cIndividuality, graceful lines,\nlovely color combinations, rich\nlooking fabrics, interesting trim\nmings\u2014all these details, which\nare decidedly feminine in char\nacter, are fashion ideas that will\nhave wide-spread acceptance\nduring the coming season.\u201d\nDiscussing the business outlook\nfor fall Mr. Parish pointed out the\nrelation between economic changes\nand fashion changes. On account\nof economic conditions people are\nmore careful about what they buy.\nThey are less willing to experi\nment with new fashions. They\ncannot afford to make fashion\nmistakes.\nb\nI w\nI .'-sr\u00df \u25a0Br9K. JB\nI BWB\nwt7&&g\u00dfK W*s\nB w z jfl Hl\nIHP t* fl Wfli\nB J \u25a0k. ~M\nfa. \u00abHr B i\u00dffe'\nBL g\niHk MPWfeoM 4\u00abS-\nm I\n1\u20221\nx Bi\n\u25a0We wjhg^feSwft^.. ,jg\u00df\u00bb V BI\nB HBH HF JH \u25a0BB a\u00df>.^...'\nH Hl B\nI ik ppi h\nII I JI Fl B\nZH Kbk\nI 1\u2019\" Irll B\nIHMI W' 11W i r*\u00ab x\nIH \u25a0\u2019a B H\nB MOWS\nf M\u25a0\u25a0 I\nK^ S\n/-'^'y. 1 Be; |g\n8 I|\nhi fl\n.^r.-:<: y 18wBr\n?9htejit; z\nfrawjft. njn\n>J \u25a0BBabw'-j-'^k-.r^-\u2022 A\nI iijuij.z \u00abir \u2014M\u2014O\u2014 'I HlM\u2014\u2014\u25a0\n\u2014lnternational Newsreel\nDON\u2019T SIGH! IT\u2019S HIS MOTHER\nRUDY VALLEE, popular radio star, came home to\nWestbrook, Me., last week for the first time since 1927.\nArriving in Portland, where his family greeted him,\nRudy was taken home to Westbrook in a motor parade.\nHere we have the star with his mother and father, Mr.\nand Mrs. Charles A. Vallee. His mother kisses him as\nhe alights from the train.\nGANNON AT SEA\nWITH BRIDE\nLONDON, July 22 (LNJB,).\u2014\nHoneymooning aboard the steam\nshio Arlanza, Madeira-bound, to\nday were Bishop James Cannon,\njr., of the Methodist Episcopal\nChurch, South and Mrs. Cannon,\nthe former Mrs. Helen H. Mc-\nCallum.\nFrom Madeira the couple will\ncontinue to Brazil before return\ning to the United States. The\nwedding was performed secretly\non July 15 at Christ Church here,\nunder a special license.\nMrs. Cannon, who gave her\nresidence as New York, has been\nBishop Cannon\u2019s secretary for\nnearly a year. She is between\n40 and 45 years old.\nShe preceded Bishop Cannon\nto England as guest of Sir Henry\nand Lady Lunn, where she\nplanned to rest until Bishop\nCannon\u2019s arrival and his subse\nquent return to America.\nThe wedding, it was believed,\nwas hastened when Mrs. Cannon\nwas advised that an ocean trip\nwould be beneficial to her health.\nHurried plans were then made\nfor the wedding.\nBishop Cannon\u2019s first wife died\nabout two years ago. He is noted\nfor his prohibition crusades and\nwas a bitter opponent of Alfred\nE. Smith as Democratic Presi\ndential nominee in 1928.\nMystery Skeleton\nGoes to Do C. Morgue\nAn examination of a skele\nton, discovered yesterday during\nthe wrecking of a shed in the\n200 block Thirtenth St. S. W\u201e\nwill be conducted today at the\nDistrict Morgue.\nThe whitened bones were dis\ncovered beneath the razed shed\nby workmen of the Heckinger\nCompany, and taken to the\nMorgue by Fourth precinct po\nlice. Dr. J. Ramsay Nevitt, coro\nner, ordered the examination.\nThe property was recently ac\nquired by the United States Gov\nernment, it was reported, and\nwas formerly occupied by Dr. E.\nCx\u00dfarstow. Pohce estimated that\nthe bones were btlrted beneath\nthe ebed approximately 20 yean.\nRUM GREW HELD\nONTARIFFACT\nNEW YORK, July 22 (1.N.5.).\nWhen ten men, captured 23 jniles\noff the New Jersey coast on a\ntug with a barge containing a\ncargo of $300,000 worth of liquor\nin tow. appear for hearing August\n4 they will not only answer to\nprohibition law violation charges\nbut also to the unusual charge\nof conspiring to violate the tariff\nact of 1930. -i\nThe basis of the latter charge\nis that the men were arrested in\nAmerican waters on a vessel\nwhich contained foreign goods\nwith no papers to show how they\ncame by the cargo. -i\nThe charge in connection with\nthe tariff act carries a penalty\nof a fine of $5,000 or two years\nin prison, or both.\nCoast guards effected the cap\nture of the men and their cargo.\nDavis Straus, of New York, was\nsaid by authorities to be the\nleader of the alleged conspirators.\nBoy, 3, Has Stroll,\nAdventure, Returns\nThree-year-old James Baldej\nson, of the 900 block Third St.\nN. E., probably wasn\u2019t lost after\nall.\nAttired in his underwear, the\nboy set out for a stroll yester\nday morning and was picked up\nat Third and H Sts; N. E., by\nNinth precinct police. Unable to\ntell police his name and address,\nhe was sent to the Receiving\nHome. His parents were located\nby police and took the young\nwanderer home last night.\nJames had only wandered a\nblock from home and could prob\nably have found his way back\nwhen he was picked up.\nWoman Shot in Groin\nIn Struggle for Gun\nGrappling for possession of a\n.22 caliber rifle during an argu\nment, according to police, Lulu\nBraxton, colored, 30, 1200 block\nLinden Court N. E., early today\nwas shot and seriously wounded.\nThe woman was taken to Freed\nmen\u2019s Hospital suffering from a\nwound in the groin.\nNinth precinct police arrested\nFrank Morris, colored, 30, also\nof Linden Court on a charge of\nassault with a dangerous weapon.\nA\n3","height":"30453","width":"24403"}}
